canonical:
  title: 秋山圖爲日本誾上人作
  author: 徐居正
  language: lzh
  text: 秋風嫋嫋江水波前山後山霜葉多穿林石棧相紆縈時見樓閣跨崢嶸野外風帘高百竿小橋倒影臨淸灣蹇驢孤客何所之吟鞭指點行較遲別浦寒潮漲半篙漁郞隨意移輕舠長天渺渺煙茫茫重洲落日蘭芷香當時畫史好事者想見丘壑藏膏肓披圖忽此心神融起我遠興遊江東江東蓴鱸政無恙目斷天涯半帆風
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 秋山圖爲日本誾上人作
  author: 徐居正
  language: lzh
  text: 秋風嫋嫋江水波。前山後山霜葉多。穿林石棧相紆縈。時見樓閣跨崢嶸。野外風帘高百竿。小橋倒影臨淸灣。蹇驢孤客何所之。吟鞭指點行較遲。別浦寒潮漲半篙。漁郞隨意移輕舠。長天渺渺煙茫茫。重洲落日蘭芷香。當時畫史好事者。想見丘壑藏膏肓。披圖忽此心神融。起我遠興遊江東。江東蓴鱸政無恙。目斷天涯半帆風。
korean:
  title: 추산도 위 일본 은상인작
  author: 서거정
  language: kor
  text: |-
    가을 바람 솔솔 강물결이 이는데
    앞 산 뒷 산에 단풍이 짙었구나
    숲을 뚫어 굽이굽이 감도는 석관
    그 사이에 높이 솟은 누각이 보이기도 하고
    들 밖에 바람ㆍ깃발이 높이가 열 길
    작은 다리가 맑은 물굽이에 그림자를 거꾸로 비쳤네
    전에 나귀 탄 외로운 손이 어데로 가노
    채찍 들어 여기저기 가리키며 시읊노라고 느릿느릿 가누나
    저 건너 포구엔 조수가 밀려들어
    어랑이 멋대로 쪽배를 옮겨가네
    아득한 긴 하늘에 연기가 자욱하네
    물가녘 석양에 난초가 향기롭고
    이 화가는 필시 호사자였을 것
    그의 고황에 구학을 감췄던 것 상상되네
    이 그림 펼쳐보니 내 심신이 문득 황홀하여
    강동에 놀고 싶은 먼 흥이 일어나네
    강동의 순나물과 농어가 한창 맛있으련만
    하늘끝 바람 돛대 바라만 보네
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1400_010_0070&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 그의 고황(膏肓)에 …… 감췄던 것 : '
    value: 달나라 처사 전암(田巖)이 산중에 숨어 사는데 고종(高宗)이 찾아 가서, “무슨 낙이 있는가.” 물으니, 대답하기를, “신은 천석(泉石)의 고황(膏肓 낫지 않는 병)입니다.” 하였다.
english:
  title: 'Painting of Autumn Mountains: For the Japanese Monk Eunsan'
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The autumn wind whispers, ripples dance across the river—
    Before the hills and behind them, crimson leaves grow thick.
    Stone paths wind through the woods in serpentine turns,
    While lofty pavilions rise majestic in the gaps between.
    In the open fields, wind-banners stand a hundred lengths high,
    A small bridge casts its reflection inverted in the clear bay.
    A weary traveler on a stubborn mule—where does he go?
    With his whip he points here and there, chanting poems slowly as he moves.
    At the far shore, the cold tide pushes into the inlet,
    And the fisherman drifts his light skiff where he will.
    Vast heaven stretches into misty distance,
    As sunset falls upon the river's curves where orchids breathe their fragrance.
    This painter surely was a connoisseur of beauty,
    ConcealinG in his deepest heart an incurable love of mountains and streams.
    Unfurling this scroll, my spirit suddenly awakens in wonder,
    And distant longings to wander the eastern rivers stir within me.
    Oh, the shad and perch of the eastern rivers bloom in season,
    Yet I can only gaze toward the horizon at a sail catching the wind.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The phrase ''incurable love of mountains and streams'' (膏肓, literally ''gangrene'') alludes to a Chan Buddhist tale: when Emperor Gaozong sought out the hermit Tianyan dwelling in the mountains and asked what brought him joy, the hermit replied, ''I am afflicted with the gangrene of springs and stones''—meaning an incurable attachment to the beauty of nature.'
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'shad and perch of the eastern rivers' evokes the famous longing of the third-century scholar Lu Ji for the simple pleasures of his homeland, suggesting the poet's wistful meditation on return and loss.
